SIMPLE: intemperate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Intemperate
<hw>In*tem`per*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>intemperatus</ets>. See <er>In-</er> not, and
<er>Temperate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Indulging any appetite or
passion to excess; immoderate in enjoyment or exertion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Specifically,</specif> <def>addicted to an
excessive or habitual use of alcoholic liquors.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Excessive; ungovernable; inordinate; violent;
immoderate; <as>as, <ex>intemperate</ex> language, zeal, etc.;
<ex>intemperate</ex> weather</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Most do taste through fond <qex>intemperate</qex> thirst.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Use not thy mouth to <qex>intemperate</qex> swearing.</q>
<rj><qau>Ecclus. xxiii. 13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intemperate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Intemperate
<hw>In*tem`per*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To
disorder.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intemperately</ent>⟦br⟧
